(94, 'Dana Meredith', 'dmeredith@sampsoncc.edu', 'dmatthews@sampsoncc.edu', 'MEC112-0A', '2016-02-15', 2.50, '', '0000-00-00', 0.00, 0.00, '', '', 'on', 2.50, 2.50, '<p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Worksheet I-11<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Cutting Unified Threads Date:_____________________<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><b><span style="font-size:12.0pt">MULTIPLE CHOICE. Choose the one alternative that bestcompletes the statement or answers the question.<o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">1) Threads are cut or chasedon the lathe with a single point tool by:  1) _______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Setting the correct feedson the quick</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">changegear box<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) Moving the carriage bymeans of the rack that is located under the front way<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Using a threading die<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) Making a series of cutsin the same groove<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">2) Sixty degree threadcutting is best done with the compound set at 29 degrees because:  2)_______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) It will swing out of theway to make the cross feed micrometer dial more visible<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) Most of the cutting isdone on the trailing edge of the tool as it is fed in, but the compound isbrought back to zero at the end of each cut causing some cutting on the leadingedge on the next pass<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Threads can be cut morequickly than with a straight infeed<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) It provides a cleanercutting action<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">3) Threading tools arechecked for accuracy on the 60</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">degreeangle by using a:  3) _______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Tool angle gage B) Thread gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Center gage D) Screw pitch gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">4) The tool is aligned withthe work: 4)_______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) With a center gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) With a thread gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) With a small square<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) By squaring the tool onthe face of the workpiece<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">5) The number of threads perinch can be checked with a: 5)_______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Ring gage B) Screw pitch gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Metric rule by counting D) Tool gage<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">6) When threading, thecarriage is moved along the ways by: 6)_______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) The hand wheel B) A gear train on a rack<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) The lead screw D) The feed rod spine or keyway<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">7) The half</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">nut should be engaged when threading odd numberedthreads when the threading dial is positioned at:  7) _______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Any line B) Only one line<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Any numbered line D) Opposite line only<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">8) For threading, thespindle should be turning:  8) _______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) At the RPM given instandard charts for the type of metal you are working on<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) At the slowest speed thelathe can be set<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) At about one</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">fourth normal turning speeds<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) None of the above<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">9) Left</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">hand threads are cut by:  9)_______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Making a right handthread and turning it end for end<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) Using a left handthreading die as these threads cannot be made on an ordinary lathe<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Turning the tool upsidedown, reversing the rotation of the spindle and moving the tool from left toright<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) Using a standard tool andsetting the compound 29.5 degrees to the left of the operator<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">10) The thread is picked upwhen a threading tool is removed for grinding by:  10)______<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">A) Replacing the tool in theholder and proceeding with threading<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">B) Replacing the tool in theholder and repositioning the tool by moving the compound and cross feed screws<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">C) Replacing the tool in theholder, engaging the half</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;font-family:TestGen;mso-bidi-font-family:TestGen">-</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt">nut andrepositioning the tool with the compound and cross feed<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">D) None of the above<o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="NormalText"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt"><o:p></o:p></p>', '', '', 0.00, '', '', 'inclement_weather', '', 'Dana Meredith', '2016-02-22', 'W. Darell Matthews', '2016-02-29', 'William J. Starling (aw)', '2016-02-29'),
