(109, 'Lew Gravis', 'lgravis@sampsoncc.edu', 'cphipps@sampsoncc.edu', 'SOC 210 HB', '2016-02-24', 1.25, '', '0000-00-00', 0.00, 0.00, 'on', '<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 12pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: Times New Roman, serif; color: rgb(89, 89, 89); background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">How are the lives oflottery winners changed? Is it a blessing or a curse? What wouldyou do if you won $50 million dollars? Write at least a three-page paperanswering the three questions posed.</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif"><o:p></o:p></span></p>', 'on', 1.25, 1.50, '<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 12pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: Times New Roman, serif; color: rgb(89, 89, 89); background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">1. Explain the fourbasic principles of social stratification.</span><span style="font-size:12.0pt;line-height:107%;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:#595959"><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">2. Distinguish between caste and class systems.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">3. Explain the role of ideology in socialstratification.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">4. Examine differences between thestructural-functional and social conflict analyses of stratification.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">5. Evaluate the Davis-Moore thesis.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">6. Suggest reasons why a Marxist revolution hasnot occurred in the advanced capitalist societies.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">7. Identify and describe Max Webers threedimensions of inequality.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">8. Be able to distinguish between thestratification characteristics of hunting and gathering, horticultural,pastoral, agrarian, and industrial societies.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">9. Explain the historical significance of KuznetsCurve in reference to stratification.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">10. Identify and describe the dimensions of socialclass in the United States.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">11. Recognize the continuing importance ofascriptive factors such as ancestry, gender, race and ethnicity, and religionin determining an individuals class placement in the United States.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">12. Characterize the four social classes in theUnited States.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">13. Examine ways in which social standing islinked to health, values, politics, and family life.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">14. Distinguish between intergenerational andintragenerational social mobility.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">15. Discuss trends in social mobility in the UnitedStates.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-position: initial; background-repeat: initial;">16. Distinguish between absolute and relativepoverty.</span><br><span style="background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-size: initial; background-origin: init